  "text": "As mentioned already, S6Ks have been shown to phosphorylate other components of the translational machinery such as eIF4B (42) and eEF2 kinase (57). It will be informative to use cells from S6K1/2 knockout animals to explore their importance in controlling specific stages in mRNA translation. Recent data have shown that S6K1 associates with the translation initiation factor eIF3 in a regulated manner. mTOR also associates with eIF3 [CITATION_1] . As discussed above, the association of S6K1 with eIF3 likely targets it to its substrate eIF4B. Interestingly, cell activation results in recruitment of the upstream regulator of S6K1, mTOR/raptor (TORC1) to eIF3, where it can presumably phosphorylate eIF4B [CITATION_2] .",
